<DOC><DOCNO> AP880503-0126 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1344EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w PM-US-Lebanon     05-03 0231</FIRST><SECOND>PM-US-Lebanon,230</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-Israel-Lebanon</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The White House, in a response to the Israeliincursion into Lebanon, today expressed concern about theincreasing level of violence in that country and called forwithdrawal of all foreign forces.   ``The United States believes there is a need for mutually agreedsecurity arrangements to assure stability and security inLebanon,'' presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.   ``We are concerned about the increasing level of violence andcall for restraint by all parties,'' Fitzwater said. ``Violencedoes not serve anyone's interest and underscores the need forcomprehensive political solutions.''   ``In this regard, the United States continues to supportLebanese unity, sovereignty and independence and the withdrawal ofall foreign forces and the extension of central governmentauthority throughout Lebanon,'' he said. ``We have consistentlysupported political reform and dialogue in Lebanon.''   ``On the broader issue of Middle East peace, we continue toconsult with the parties involved,'' he said. ``To date, we havenot heard anyone say no. This is a positive sign in itself. We willcontinue to work for peace.''   Asked why the statement was being issued, Fitzwater said, ``It'sa response to the incursion.''   Israeli tanks pushed to within a few miles of Syrian troops insouth Lebanon today as heavily armed Israeli soldiers searched forPalestinian guerrillas in the area's rugged hills in an operationthat began Monday night.</TEXT></DOC>